{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586755"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:38:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:38:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15095"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15095"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.07,0.49,0.05,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7783"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64488"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7783"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49920"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18993"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64488"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EStruvite stones, also known as magnesium ammonium phosphate stones, form in the urinary tract under specific biochemical conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following microorganisms is most likely to cause struvite stone formation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Escherichia coli","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Proteus mirabilis","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Staphylococcus aureus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EStruvite stones form in alkaline urine, typically due to urinary tract infections with urease-producing bacteria. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EProteus mirabilis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause, as it produces large amounts of urease which splits urea into ammonia and carbon dioxide. The ammonia makes the urine alkaline, promoting crystal formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E can produce urease but rarely causes urinary tract infections. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E, despite being the most common cause of urinary tract infections, does not produce urease. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E can cause urinary tract infections but are not significant urease producers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Struvite (magnesium ammonium phosphate) stones form in alkaline urine produced by urease-positive bacteria, particularly Proteus species.","Urease-producing bacteria split urea into ammonia, creating an alkaline environment that promotes struvite crystal formation."],"references":["Flannigan RK, Battison A, De S, Humphreys MR, Bader M, Lellig E, Monga M, Chew BH, Lange D. Evaluating factors that dictate struvite stone composition: A multi-institutional clinical experience from the EDGE Research Consortium. Can Urol Assoc J. 2018 Apr;12(4):131-136. doi: 10.5489/cuaj.4804. Epub 2017 Dec 22. PMID: 29319486; PMCID: PMC5905542.","Razi A, Ghiaei A, Dolatabadi FK, Haghighi R. Unraveling the association of bacteria and urinary stones in patients with urolithiasis: an update review article. Front Med (Lausanne). 2024 Aug 30;11:1401808. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2024.1401808. PMID: 39281813; PMCID: PMC11392849.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Peerapen P, Thongboonkerd V. Kidney Stone Prevention. Adv Nutr. 2023 May;14(3):555-569. doi: 10.1016/j.advnut.2023.03.002. Epub 2023 Mar 9. PMID: 36906146; PMCID: PMC10201681"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49920"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15095"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49920"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T17:45:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T17:45:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7783"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64488"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7